<subSubSection pageId="32" pageNumber="33" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="32.[151,1437,799,969]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,267,799,825]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Remarks.</emphasis>
This group is characterized by a peculiar character, unique in the genus: male pygidium without transverse ridge (
<figureCitation box="[223,321,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 121–124" captionStartId="36.[151,264,1128,1152]" captionTargetBox="[157,1429,420,1104]" captionTargetId="figure-129@36.[157,1429,420,1104]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURES 121–124. Male pygidium and female ventrite 5 of Tychius. Male pygidium:121. T. morawitzi group; 122. T. bajtenovi group. Female ventrite 5: 123. T. kaszabi; 124. T. crassifemoris." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4411339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4411339/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 122</figureCitation>
). Otherwise it should be related to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Becker" authorityYear="1864" box="[747,886,835,860]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Tychius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morawitzi">
<emphasis box="[747,886,835,860]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">T. morawitzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (
<figureCitation box="[972,1067,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 121–124" captionStartId="36.[151,264,1128,1152]" captionTargetBox="[157,1429,420,1104]" captionTargetId="figure-129@36.[157,1429,420,1104]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURES 121–124. Male pygidium and female ventrite 5 of Tychius. Male pygidium:121. T. morawitzi group; 122. T. bajtenovi group. Female ventrite 5: 123. T. kaszabi; 124. T. crassifemoris." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4411339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4411339/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 121</figureCitation>
) as suggested by the shape of the genitalia (especially in the female). It clearly differs from this group by the seven segments of the antennal funicle cylindrical and lacking broad scales and the absence of seta-like scales on pronotum and elytra. All the species probably feed on 
<taxonomicName box="[348,477,943,969]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Hedysarum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[348,477,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Hedysarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
